1
00:00:01,448 --> 00:00:03,000
[upbeat music]

2
00:00:36,344 --> 00:00:38,758
[Man laughs] Come here.

3
00:01:06,137 --> 00:01:07,758
[Man] Mmm.

4
00:01:07,827 --> 00:01:10,896
[woman pants]

5
00:01:10,965 --> 00:01:12,241
You're so pretty.

6
00:01:17,413 --> 00:01:18,689
[music playing on car]

7
00:01:30,896 --> 00:01:32,275
[Michelle] Unbelievable.

8
00:01:32,344 --> 00:01:34,137
How many times I've...

9
00:01:35,931 --> 00:01:37,758
I wasn't trying to
embarrass you.

10
00:01:37,827 --> 00:01:39,137
I was just giving you a clue.

11
00:01:39,206 --> 00:01:40,448
[Robert] I felt like an idiot
in front of everyone.

12
00:01:40,517 --> 00:01:42,344
How am I supposed to know
who wrote "The Stranger"?

13
00:01:42,413 --> 00:01:44,379
But nobody cares that
you didn't know the answer.

14
00:01:44,448 --> 00:01:45,758
[Robert] I don't know why do
we play that stupid game

15
00:01:45,827 --> 00:01:47,103
every time we go to
their house, anyway.

16
00:01:47,172 --> 00:01:48,206
It gives Vince a chance

17
00:01:48,275 --> 00:01:50,689
to waive his college
degree in my face.

18
00:01:50,758 --> 00:01:53,379
Could've at least
have stayed for dessert.

19
00:01:53,448 --> 00:01:56,482
♪ Something a little
more than time to kill ♪

20
00:01:56,551 --> 00:02:01,103
♪ There's no mistaking the
laws that we're breaking ♪

21
00:02:01,172 --> 00:02:05,172
♪ We'll do what we always do ♪

22
00:02:05,241 --> 00:02:08,758
[man chuckling]

23
00:02:08,827 --> 00:02:10,448
Hey...

24
00:02:10,517 --> 00:02:12,965
you scared
the hell outta me.

25
00:02:16,896 --> 00:02:19,344
Laura, I wanna see you
in the other room. [sighs]

26
00:02:19,413 --> 00:02:20,275
[Laura sighs]

27
00:02:20,344 --> 00:02:20,896
Get dressed and
get out of here.

28
00:02:20,965 --> 00:02:22,241
[Laura] Dad!

29
00:02:24,310 --> 00:02:25,344
[Laura sighs]

30
00:02:31,965 --> 00:02:33,413
We weren't doing anything.

31
00:02:33,482 --> 00:02:35,586
How much have
you had to drink?

32
00:02:35,655 --> 00:02:36,827
A little.

33
00:02:36,896 --> 00:02:39,206
I told you I never wanted
to see him here again.

34
00:02:39,275 --> 00:02:40,827
You completely disobeyed me.

35
00:02:40,896 --> 00:02:43,172
You never got mad
when I was with Danny.

36
00:02:43,241 --> 00:02:45,000
Is it that you don't like Eric?
Because--

37
00:02:45,068 --> 00:02:48,379
Danny would never have
been in there like that.

38
00:02:48,448 --> 00:02:49,862
Oh, you just never caught us.

39
00:02:53,620 --> 00:02:55,379
This is not about which
boyfriend we like better.

40
00:02:55,448 --> 00:02:58,000
This is about trusting
you when we're away.

41
00:02:58,068 --> 00:02:59,586
You're grounded for
two weeks for this.

42
00:02:59,655 --> 00:03:00,517
-Mother, what--?
-[Robert] Go to bed!

43
00:03:00,586 --> 00:03:02,620
Sleep it off!

44
00:03:02,689 --> 00:03:05,068
[Laura sighs]

45
00:03:07,413 --> 00:03:08,379
This is getting out of hand.

46
00:03:08,448 --> 00:03:10,896
I'm too tired to
get into this now.

47
00:03:10,965 --> 00:03:12,275
I'm going to bed.

48
00:03:12,344 --> 00:03:14,517
Right.

49
00:03:14,586 --> 00:03:15,827
Are you coming?

50
00:03:15,896 --> 00:03:17,724
In a while.

51
00:03:23,793 --> 00:03:26,551
[birds chirping]

52
00:03:28,448 --> 00:03:29,793
Well, I'd promised
to be harder, Steve

53
00:03:29,862 --> 00:03:31,724
when business picks up, but

54
00:03:31,793 --> 00:03:33,310
on what if business
doesn't pick up.

55
00:03:33,379 --> 00:03:34,793
Have you seen my briefcase?

56
00:03:34,862 --> 00:03:35,896
Oh, here it is.

57
00:03:43,379 --> 00:03:44,793
Listen Laura, some stupid stuff

58
00:03:44,862 --> 00:03:45,896
like the one you
pulled last night,

59
00:03:45,965 --> 00:03:48,275
have got to stop, do
you understand me?

60
00:03:48,344 --> 00:03:49,896
You know how critical
your senior year

61
00:03:49,965 --> 00:03:51,965
is to getting into
the right college.

62
00:03:53,758 --> 00:03:54,827
Now we have four weeks

63
00:03:54,896 --> 00:03:56,413
to send in those letters
of recommendation.

64
00:03:56,482 --> 00:03:58,310
You're on top of those, right?

65
00:03:58,379 --> 00:04:00,275
Yes.

66
00:04:00,344 --> 00:04:02,827
I'm not gonna do all
this by myself you know.

67
00:04:02,896 --> 00:04:05,620
Tonight we work on
Northwestern's and Wisconsin's,

68
00:04:05,689 --> 00:04:07,310
I'm counting on you young lady.

69
00:04:10,172 --> 00:04:11,137
[sighs]

70
00:04:13,103 --> 00:04:15,068
Maybe we all hold onto them
until the end of the month.

71
00:04:15,137 --> 00:04:16,551
Maybe things will pick up.

72
00:04:19,862 --> 00:04:21,172
I'm showing a house at 5:30

73
00:04:21,241 --> 00:04:22,689
but I should be home
in time to make dinner.

74
00:04:22,758 --> 00:04:25,103
I'm going to work.

75
00:04:25,172 --> 00:04:26,275
This time I promise.

76
00:04:28,517 --> 00:04:29,241
I'll see you later.

77
00:04:29,310 --> 00:04:30,068
Uh-huh

78
00:04:30,137 --> 00:04:31,862
God, I'm late.

79
00:04:31,931 --> 00:04:32,827
So am I.

80
00:04:34,827 --> 00:04:35,827
Don't forget your lunch.

81
00:04:35,896 --> 00:04:37,586
I'll just grab
something at school.

82
00:04:37,655 --> 00:04:39,241
Try not to make
it french fries.

83
00:04:42,896 --> 00:04:44,344
[sighs]

84
00:04:44,413 --> 00:04:45,896
[bell rings]

85
00:04:45,965 --> 00:04:48,448
[chattering]

86
00:04:58,620 --> 00:05:00,931
[Man] Laura, can I speak to you?

87
00:05:04,206 --> 00:05:07,206
You didn't turn in
yesterday's assignments.

88
00:05:07,275 --> 00:05:09,275
You flunked the midterm, Laura.

89
00:05:09,344 --> 00:05:10,793
I don't know if I can
let you make it up.

90
00:05:10,862 --> 00:05:12,275
I mean, you're so far behind.

91
00:05:12,344 --> 00:05:13,137
I understand.

92
00:05:13,206 --> 00:05:14,551
I don't.

93
00:05:14,620 --> 00:05:17,413
You were one of the top
students in my class last year.

94
00:05:17,482 --> 00:05:19,965
Look, I know what your
brother went through

95
00:05:20,034 --> 00:05:22,827
and I just don't wanna see
you start down the same path.

96
00:05:22,896 --> 00:05:24,310
I'm just burnt
out, that's all.

97
00:05:24,379 --> 00:05:27,275
I've talked to Mr. Carlson
about this.

98
00:05:27,344 --> 00:05:29,689
I'm required to tell him
when things slide this far,

99
00:05:29,758 --> 00:05:31,482
you know the policy.

100
00:05:31,551 --> 00:05:34,172
Yeah, whatever. I'm
late for calculus.

101
00:05:37,275 --> 00:05:41,448
[chattering]

102
00:05:41,517 --> 00:05:43,137
[Boy] Hey you.

103
00:05:43,206 --> 00:05:44,241
[Eric] You spilled.

104
00:05:44,310 --> 00:05:45,413
You okay?

105
00:05:47,413 --> 00:05:50,000
You ever wonder what would
be like to be somebody else?

106
00:05:52,206 --> 00:05:54,068
Someone else.
What do you mean?

107
00:05:54,137 --> 00:05:56,517
Somebody else,
somebody different,

108
00:05:56,586 --> 00:05:58,103
different family,

109
00:05:58,172 --> 00:06:00,965
different schools,
different looks.

110
00:06:01,034 --> 00:06:02,206
Everything.

111
00:06:02,275 --> 00:06:04,482
I don't get it, how
could you be someone else?

112
00:06:06,448 --> 00:06:07,379
Forget it.

113
00:06:07,448 --> 00:06:08,655
No, you gotta give
it a rest Laura.

114
00:06:08,724 --> 00:06:10,758
You've been talking
crazy lately.

115
00:06:10,827 --> 00:06:12,000
Really.

116
00:06:13,620 --> 00:06:15,517
Well, maybe I'm crazy.

117
00:06:17,551 --> 00:06:19,275
Hey, isn't that
dad over there?

118
00:06:22,827 --> 00:06:25,068
[Eric] Don't tell me it's
his cousin, right?

119
00:06:30,827 --> 00:06:34,068
-Get outta here.
-[Eric chuckles]

120
00:06:34,137 --> 00:06:35,379
[door opens]

121
00:06:46,758 --> 00:06:47,793
[Michelle on answering machine]
Hi, it looks like

122
00:06:47,862 --> 00:06:49,000
I'm not gonna
make it home after all.

123
00:06:49,068 --> 00:06:50,689
I know, don't say it.

124
00:06:50,758 --> 00:06:53,448
Hmm-- The Northwestern
application is in my desk,

125
00:06:53,517 --> 00:06:55,655
why don't you get started
I'll arrive after dinner...

126
00:06:55,724 --> 00:06:57,172
[Robert] Laura? Is that you?

127
00:06:57,241 --> 00:06:58,931
[Michelle on answering machine]
...lamb chops are defrosting.

128
00:06:59,000 --> 00:07:00,517
-Yeah?
-[answering machine beeps]

129
00:07:00,586 --> 00:07:02,137
[Robert]
Come in here, we need to talk.

130
00:07:11,344 --> 00:07:13,724
So is there something
you wanna tell me?

131
00:07:16,310 --> 00:07:17,413
No. Why?

132
00:07:19,379 --> 00:07:21,103
Well, I got a call from
your guidance counselor,

133
00:07:21,172 --> 00:07:23,413
Mr. Carlson?

134
00:07:23,482 --> 00:07:25,344
He says you're barely
passing any of your classes,

135
00:07:25,413 --> 00:07:27,862
you've been ditching school.

136
00:07:27,931 --> 00:07:29,965
He wants to see your mother
and me Wednesday afternoon.

137
00:07:30,034 --> 00:07:31,000
I--

138
00:07:33,241 --> 00:07:35,379
Dad, don't worry. I'm not
gonna flunk any of my classes.

139
00:07:35,448 --> 00:07:36,586
This is exactly
how David started.

140
00:07:36,655 --> 00:07:37,793
First its the grades,
then its the---

141
00:07:37,862 --> 00:07:39,517
Dad, I'm not stealing
things or doing drugs,

142
00:07:39,586 --> 00:07:40,758
why don't you just lay off?

143
00:07:40,827 --> 00:07:43,344
We have a serious,
serious problem here, Laura.

144
00:07:43,413 --> 00:07:45,689
What are we gonna do about it?

145
00:07:45,758 --> 00:07:46,827
Nothing, just don't worry.

146
00:07:46,896 --> 00:07:47,724
Don't worry.

147
00:07:47,793 --> 00:07:48,758
Well, that's just great.

148
00:07:48,827 --> 00:07:50,137
You tell that to your mother.

149
00:07:50,206 --> 00:07:51,862
She's only been helping
you fill out applications

150
00:07:51,931 --> 00:07:53,241
for college for the last month.

151
00:07:53,310 --> 00:07:56,448
I never asked her to help
me fill out those applications

152
00:07:56,517 --> 00:07:57,344
[sighs]

153
00:07:57,413 --> 00:07:59,241
Laura!

154
00:07:59,310 --> 00:08:01,206
Hey, Laura,
get back here!

155
00:08:06,862 --> 00:08:10,310
[chattering and music
from inside]

156
00:08:15,000 --> 00:08:16,206
[Laura] I couldn't really
get you that much

157
00:08:16,275 --> 00:08:17,620
because mom didn't have time
to go to the store

158
00:08:17,689 --> 00:08:22,137
and I was doing some stuff,
not like lying on the couch.

159
00:08:22,206 --> 00:08:26,172
Cool, I could use those, thanks.
How things in squirrel cage?

160
00:08:26,241 --> 00:08:29,896
Don't ask, I feel like I
can't breathe in that house.

161
00:08:29,965 --> 00:08:32,034
[David] What's up?

162
00:08:32,103 --> 00:08:33,413
I just can't wait
to get out of there.

163
00:08:33,482 --> 00:08:36,758
All mom talks about is, what
college am I gonna go to.

164
00:08:36,827 --> 00:08:37,862
She makes such
a big deal about me

165
00:08:37,931 --> 00:08:39,931
being first and
the family to go.

166
00:08:40,000 --> 00:08:41,724
I guess I kind of left
that on you, didn't I ?

167
00:08:41,793 --> 00:08:43,724
Yeah, I think.

168
00:08:43,793 --> 00:08:46,172
If I hear mom saying she's
counting on me one more time,

169
00:08:46,241 --> 00:08:48,448
I think I'm gonna explode.

170
00:08:48,517 --> 00:08:50,413
I should be so lucky.

171
00:08:50,482 --> 00:08:52,551
What do you mean?

172
00:08:52,620 --> 00:08:55,586
Mom never said
anything like that to me.

173
00:08:55,655 --> 00:08:57,724
When I was about 13,
I guess, Bill Turner and I

174
00:08:57,793 --> 00:09:01,517
broke into dad's liquor
cabinet after school.

175
00:09:01,586 --> 00:09:02,862
We drank a whole
bottle of his bourbon,

176
00:09:02,931 --> 00:09:04,034
it was the first
time I ever drank.

177
00:09:04,103 --> 00:09:05,103
I was so wasted.

178
00:09:05,172 --> 00:09:06,241
[chuckles]

179
00:09:06,310 --> 00:09:07,793
Mom came home early
and busted us.

180
00:09:07,862 --> 00:09:09,896
And after she sent Bill home,
she came up to my room

181
00:09:09,965 --> 00:09:13,034
with this really serious
look on her face.

182
00:09:13,103 --> 00:09:15,758
I was pretty scared.

183
00:09:15,827 --> 00:09:18,206
And she said, "David...

184
00:09:18,275 --> 00:09:21,000
I always knew you were gonna
be the loser in this family.

185
00:09:23,068 --> 00:09:24,172
I don't think she meant it.

186
00:09:24,241 --> 00:09:25,413
Oh yeah, she did.

187
00:09:25,482 --> 00:09:26,793
[clattering]

188
00:09:26,862 --> 00:09:27,724
And that wasn't the last time

189
00:09:27,793 --> 00:09:30,655
I heard that from her either.

190
00:09:30,724 --> 00:09:31,724
And after that,
and I don't know,

191
00:09:31,793 --> 00:09:33,551
I just started getting
in trouble a lot.

192
00:09:33,620 --> 00:09:35,172
Nothing seemed to
matter anymore.

193
00:09:36,862 --> 00:09:38,551
But hey, getting
outta that house

194
00:09:38,620 --> 00:09:40,586
was the best thing I ever did.

195
00:09:40,655 --> 00:09:42,482
Now that I got a
job and everything,

196
00:09:42,551 --> 00:09:44,655
I'm gonna get my own place.

197
00:09:44,724 --> 00:09:46,275
That's what you
said last time.

198
00:09:46,344 --> 00:09:48,034
This time I'm serious.

199
00:09:48,103 --> 00:09:49,137
Besides, Stuart said

200
00:09:49,206 --> 00:09:50,137
I can only stay in
the back of the shop

201
00:09:50,206 --> 00:09:52,827
till the end of the month.

202
00:09:52,896 --> 00:09:54,965
Guess I'm running out
of friends to hit up.

203
00:09:57,689 --> 00:09:59,896
Or you can always
come back home.

204
00:09:59,965 --> 00:10:01,344
Yeah. Right
that'll be the day.

205
00:10:02,965 --> 00:10:04,482
Yeah. I guess this is
not a very good idea.

206
00:10:06,379 --> 00:10:08,689
Real bad idea.

207
00:10:08,758 --> 00:10:09,793
[sighs]

208
00:10:12,724 --> 00:10:15,827
[door closes]

209
00:10:15,896 --> 00:10:17,655
-[Michelle] Where have you been?
-Out

210
00:10:17,724 --> 00:10:19,758
Out where? You're grounded?

211
00:10:19,827 --> 00:10:22,241
You saw David, didn't you?

212
00:10:22,310 --> 00:10:24,379
Ah-- He's my brother, I'm
allowed to see him, aren't I?

213
00:10:24,448 --> 00:10:25,896
How are you planning
to get into college

214
00:10:25,965 --> 00:10:27,310
without finishing
high school first?

215
00:10:27,379 --> 00:10:28,689
I plan on finishing
high school.

216
00:10:28,758 --> 00:10:30,172
Not with F's and
all your classes.

217
00:10:30,241 --> 00:10:30,896
I'm not getting F's
in all my classes.

218
00:10:30,965 --> 00:10:32,068
Don't lie to me!

219
00:10:32,137 --> 00:10:33,931
What the hell has
gotten into you?

220
00:10:34,000 --> 00:10:35,206
Do you wanna end up
like your brother?

221
00:10:35,275 --> 00:10:36,689
Do you wanna throw
your life away?

222
00:10:36,758 --> 00:10:38,000
He hasn't thrown
his life away.

223
00:10:38,068 --> 00:10:39,448
He's got a good job now.

224
00:10:39,517 --> 00:10:41,413
Right, washing dishes?

225
00:10:41,482 --> 00:10:42,586
You're such a snob.

226
00:10:42,655 --> 00:10:44,137
Listen to me.
Is that what you want?

227
00:10:44,206 --> 00:10:45,931
Because that is exactly
how you're gonna end up

228
00:10:46,000 --> 00:10:47,206
if you don't get into
a decent college.

229
00:10:47,275 --> 00:10:48,586
Maybe I won't go
to college next fall.

230
00:10:48,655 --> 00:10:50,517
Maybe I won't go
to college at all.

231
00:10:50,586 --> 00:10:51,689
[Michelle sighs]

232
00:10:51,758 --> 00:10:53,241
You don't even know
what you're saying.

233
00:10:53,310 --> 00:10:54,241
Go to bed.

234
00:10:54,310 --> 00:10:56,000
We'll talk about
this in the morning.

235
00:10:56,068 --> 00:10:57,068
[sighs hard]

236
00:10:59,413 --> 00:11:02,862
[Counselor] Has she been moody,
secretive, depressed lately,

237
00:11:02,931 --> 00:11:04,862
hanging out with
different friends?

238
00:11:04,931 --> 00:11:07,172
Yes. All of those things.

239
00:11:07,241 --> 00:11:08,758
Just to say, we're
very concerned.

240
00:11:10,448 --> 00:11:12,275
Well, I know that we
discussed this option

241
00:11:12,344 --> 00:11:13,344
when you were having
problems with David

242
00:11:13,413 --> 00:11:14,862
and I understood
your reluctance then

243
00:11:14,931 --> 00:11:16,862
but a residential
treatment facility,

244
00:11:16,931 --> 00:11:20,068
such as Meadowbrook has
been having terrific success

245
00:11:20,137 --> 00:11:23,241
in dealing with these types
of behavior disorders.

246
00:11:23,310 --> 00:11:24,758
You might want to reconsider

247
00:11:24,827 --> 00:11:26,827
getting some professional
help this time.

248
00:11:26,896 --> 00:11:29,655
I have to tell you, I feel
very uncomfortable about this.

249
00:11:29,724 --> 00:11:30,896
I still like to
think that we could

250
00:11:30,965 --> 00:11:32,793
handle any problems ourselves.

251
00:11:32,862 --> 00:11:36,206
I understand, but I do
have to be honest with you.

252
00:11:36,275 --> 00:11:39,862
I've seen these types of
sudden behavior changes in kids

253
00:11:39,931 --> 00:11:42,896
and oftentimes it's
a cry for help.

254
00:11:42,965 --> 00:11:44,103
If that cry goes unheard,

255
00:11:44,172 --> 00:11:47,413
it could lead to self
destructive behavior.

256
00:11:47,482 --> 00:11:50,379
Nowadays with teen suicides
at epidemic proportions,

257
00:11:50,448 --> 00:11:52,827
I just think we all
have to look closer

258
00:11:52,896 --> 00:11:54,620
at these types of warning signs.

259
00:11:58,379 --> 00:12:02,241
[dramatic music]

260
00:12:27,241 --> 00:12:30,448
Robert come up here now!

261
00:12:42,206 --> 00:12:43,310
Where'd you find those?

262
00:12:43,379 --> 00:12:44,655
In her desk.

263
00:12:44,724 --> 00:12:46,724
Well what were you
doing in her desk?

264
00:12:46,793 --> 00:12:49,827
Looking for something,
drugs, anything answers.

265
00:12:51,310 --> 00:12:53,137
-Well it's only a poem...
-[Michelle] Read it.

266
00:12:57,310 --> 00:12:59,482
[reading] Feeling so small,

267
00:12:59,551 --> 00:13:01,068
but I know it'd be
better for everyone.

268
00:13:01,137 --> 00:13:04,000
If I just wasn't here at all.

269
00:13:04,068 --> 00:13:07,862
Just a poem huh?

270
00:13:07,931 --> 00:13:09,103
[Michelle sighs heavy]

271
00:13:09,172 --> 00:13:12,448
Well, she couldn't really
be talking about suicide.

272
00:13:12,517 --> 00:13:13,724
[door closes]

273
00:13:16,965 --> 00:13:18,241
I'm going to talk to her.

274
00:13:22,724 --> 00:13:26,103
[footsteps approaching]

275
00:13:26,172 --> 00:13:27,310
Hi.

276
00:13:27,379 --> 00:13:28,482
How was school?

277
00:13:28,551 --> 00:13:29,379
Fine.

278
00:13:31,724 --> 00:13:33,689
Can we talk for a minute?

279
00:13:33,758 --> 00:13:34,862
Sure.

280
00:13:40,724 --> 00:13:42,586
I know we've had
our problems lately

281
00:13:44,103 --> 00:13:46,448
but I want you to know
that you can always come

282
00:13:46,517 --> 00:13:49,068
and talk to me about anything.

283
00:13:49,137 --> 00:13:51,724
No matter how bad it is.

284
00:13:51,793 --> 00:13:52,827
Yeah. I know that.

285
00:13:57,551 --> 00:14:01,896
I know breaking up with
Danny was tough on you

286
00:14:01,965 --> 00:14:07,241
and sometimes it's good
to talk about that stuff.

287
00:14:07,310 --> 00:14:09,689
Eh-- If you feel like talking
about it and you can.

288
00:14:09,758 --> 00:14:10,931
[smiles nervously]

289
00:14:11,000 --> 00:14:12,275
I would like it if you did.

290
00:14:15,000 --> 00:14:16,103
I remember when I broke up

291
00:14:16,172 --> 00:14:19,000
with this guy in high
school, Dev Warner.

292
00:14:19,068 --> 00:14:20,758
I thought I was gonna die.

293
00:14:23,965 --> 00:14:27,517
I'm fine. I really don't
need to talk about it.

294
00:14:27,586 --> 00:14:29,068
Are you sure?

295
00:14:30,551 --> 00:14:31,724
Yeah.

296
00:14:35,793 --> 00:14:37,310
Well...

297
00:14:37,379 --> 00:14:39,034
I just wanted
you to know that

298
00:14:39,103 --> 00:14:40,413
I'm always here for you.

299
00:14:42,517 --> 00:14:44,310
I'm not gonna do my homework.

300
00:14:44,379 --> 00:14:46,620
I'm grounded, remember?

301
00:14:57,620 --> 00:14:59,655
Michelle, look at this.

302
00:14:59,724 --> 00:15:00,965
What is it?

303
00:15:02,965 --> 00:15:05,827
It says here that
Laura never took the SAT's?

304
00:15:05,896 --> 00:15:07,137
What?

305
00:15:07,206 --> 00:15:08,620
No, this is a mistake.

306
00:15:12,172 --> 00:15:13,206
I'll call the school.

307
00:15:15,310 --> 00:15:17,000
[Michelle sighs heavy]

308
00:15:32,000 --> 00:15:33,379
Mom, what are you doing?

309
00:15:35,689 --> 00:15:38,517
When were you planning
to tell us about the SATs?

310
00:15:40,379 --> 00:15:42,000
Eh-- I was gonna tell you--

311
00:15:42,068 --> 00:15:43,793
No.

312
00:15:43,862 --> 00:15:45,689
no more excuses,

313
00:15:45,758 --> 00:15:47,655
no more explanations.

314
00:15:47,724 --> 00:15:48,793
I don't wanna see you now,

315
00:15:48,862 --> 00:15:50,275
I don't wanna hear your voice.

316
00:15:55,793 --> 00:15:56,758
Okay. I'm just gonna go--

317
00:15:56,827 --> 00:15:59,448
I don't care
where you're going.

318
00:15:59,517 --> 00:16:01,517
I don't know if I can
ever forgive you for this.

319
00:16:08,034 --> 00:16:12,172
[defiant music]

320
00:16:23,241 --> 00:16:25,448
[car starts]

321
00:16:25,517 --> 00:16:27,793
[car skids]

322
00:16:32,724 --> 00:16:35,172
[TV on]

323
00:16:41,724 --> 00:16:44,137
[Laura] I can't believe
how stupid I am.

324
00:16:47,310 --> 00:16:48,724
I've never seen her like that.

325
00:16:48,793 --> 00:16:49,689
Uh-huh.

326
00:16:49,758 --> 00:16:51,517
I can't go home.

327
00:16:51,586 --> 00:16:53,310
My roommate is not coming
home until Thursday

328
00:16:53,379 --> 00:16:56,517
so you can stay here.

329
00:16:56,586 --> 00:16:57,931
It's late.

330
00:16:58,000 --> 00:16:59,068
Let's go to bed.

331
00:17:00,689 --> 00:17:04,448
Well, why don't I
sleep on the couch.

332
00:17:04,517 --> 00:17:06,482
What's wrong?

333
00:17:06,551 --> 00:17:07,862
[chuckles]

334
00:17:07,931 --> 00:17:09,965
I just told you
that I can't go home.

335
00:17:10,034 --> 00:17:10,965
Uh-huh.

336
00:17:11,034 --> 00:17:14,413
And my life is
totally messed up.

337
00:17:14,482 --> 00:17:15,896
Look, I just need
a friend right now.

338
00:17:15,965 --> 00:17:17,620
Hey, I am your friend.

339
00:17:19,275 --> 00:17:20,931
I'm the best friend
that you've got.

340
00:17:22,448 --> 00:17:24,931
Look, I said no,
just leave me alone.

341
00:17:25,000 --> 00:17:26,448
This is the
perfect opportunity.

342
00:17:26,517 --> 00:17:28,137
We got the whole
place to ourselves.

343
00:17:28,206 --> 00:17:29,896
I can't believe that's
all you're interested in.

344
00:17:29,965 --> 00:17:31,793
[sighs heavy]

345
00:17:31,862 --> 00:17:32,793
You never cared about me.

346
00:17:32,862 --> 00:17:34,689
Oh don't be so selfish.

347
00:17:34,758 --> 00:17:35,896
What I'm doing here.

348
00:17:35,965 --> 00:17:37,000
What about me?

349
00:17:37,068 --> 00:17:38,586
What about you?

350
00:17:40,482 --> 00:17:43,310
[dramatic music]

351
00:17:56,275 --> 00:17:59,172
[passing car honks]

352
00:18:03,620 --> 00:18:05,034
[tires screeching]

353
00:18:11,034 --> 00:18:11,931
[passing car honks]

354
00:18:12,000 --> 00:18:15,172
[tires screeching]

355
00:18:17,620 --> 00:18:20,793
[loud crash]

356
00:18:23,931 --> 00:18:30,275
[police radio chatter]

357
00:18:42,931 --> 00:18:44,172
Are you sure you all right?

358
00:18:44,241 --> 00:18:45,413
Dad, I told you I'm fine.

359
00:18:45,482 --> 00:18:46,620
Yeah, the officer said

360
00:18:46,689 --> 00:18:49,103
that your blood alcohol
level was very high.

361
00:18:49,172 --> 00:18:51,413
You probably know that
we've made a decision.

362
00:18:51,482 --> 00:18:52,793
We're gonna get you some help.

363
00:18:52,862 --> 00:18:54,793
We're sending you to a
place called Meadowbrook.

364
00:18:54,862 --> 00:19:01,413
[dramatic music]

365
00:19:16,586 --> 00:19:18,068
[Dr. Winslow] Self esteem,

366
00:19:18,137 --> 00:19:21,275
life management
skills, leadership qualities.

367
00:19:21,344 --> 00:19:23,655
These are the goals
of Meadowbrook.

368
00:19:23,724 --> 00:19:27,482
Now we don't know yet,
the extent of Laura's problem.

369
00:19:29,103 --> 00:19:32,034
The behavior you have seen
may be the tip of the iceberg,

370
00:19:32,103 --> 00:19:34,275
or it may just be growing pains.

371
00:19:34,344 --> 00:19:37,620
But I assure you, our success
rate here is impressive.

372
00:19:37,689 --> 00:19:39,689
Often the two week evaluation
period is more than enough

373
00:19:39,758 --> 00:19:42,068
to take care of the problem.

374
00:19:42,137 --> 00:19:44,896
At Meadowbrook we really
do turn lives around.

375
00:19:44,965 --> 00:19:45,896
[knocks]

376
00:19:45,965 --> 00:19:47,034
[Dr. Winslow] Yes.

377
00:19:51,482 --> 00:19:52,620
Thank you.

378
00:19:57,896 --> 00:19:58,965
Very good.

379
00:19:59,034 --> 00:20:02,172
Your insurance is
more than adequate.

380
00:20:02,241 --> 00:20:04,517
[sighs heavily]

381
00:20:04,586 --> 00:20:06,655
[Robert]
I love you, sweetheart.

382
00:20:06,724 --> 00:20:08,793
I can't believe
you're doing this to me.

383
00:20:08,862 --> 00:20:11,965
I hope you understand we want
what's best for you sweetie.

384
00:20:12,034 --> 00:20:14,620
Don't even try mom.

385
00:20:14,689 --> 00:20:16,310
[steps walking away]

386
00:20:19,586 --> 00:20:23,413
[sad music]

387
00:20:34,586 --> 00:20:37,655
[sighs heavily]

388
00:20:37,724 --> 00:20:40,586
They admitted here
without even talking to her.

389
00:20:40,655 --> 00:20:41,931
What?

390
00:20:42,000 --> 00:20:44,172
They admitted her without
seeing her, without a diagnosis.

391
00:20:44,241 --> 00:20:45,931
How could they do that?

392
00:20:46,000 --> 00:20:48,517
Well, what did they say to
the insurance companies?

393
00:20:48,586 --> 00:20:49,586
It will be all right?

394
00:20:49,655 --> 00:20:51,241
It's just two weeks.

395
00:20:51,310 --> 00:20:52,793
The important thing is
she's getting help.

396
00:21:09,655 --> 00:21:12,034
Dr Winslow, I don't know
what my parents told you,

397
00:21:12,103 --> 00:21:15,137
but I really don't belong here.

398
00:21:15,206 --> 00:21:18,965
You know Laura, I think it best
that the time that you are here

399
00:21:19,034 --> 00:21:21,241
that you try to
make the most of it.

400
00:21:21,310 --> 00:21:24,000
Consider it a break
for you and your parents.

401
00:21:24,068 --> 00:21:26,275
Time to sort things out.

402
00:21:26,344 --> 00:21:27,896
-Okay.
-[Dr. Winslow] Okay.

403
00:21:27,965 --> 00:21:31,206
This is Ms. Collins.
She'll help you settle in.

404
00:21:31,275 --> 00:21:32,379
-All right?
-Okay.

405
00:21:32,448 --> 00:21:33,931
All right.

406
00:21:35,724 --> 00:21:37,413
[door-lock opens]

407
00:21:45,448 --> 00:21:47,034
[door closes loudly]

408
00:22:11,448 --> 00:22:13,275
[Nurse] Sit here.

409
00:22:13,344 --> 00:22:14,448
What's that for?

410
00:22:14,517 --> 00:22:16,586
It's procedure,
everybody gets it.

411
00:22:16,655 --> 00:22:19,034
[Ms. Collins]
It's just something
to relax you.

412
00:22:19,103 --> 00:22:20,586
What are you doing
with my clothes?

413
00:22:20,655 --> 00:22:21,586
They're inappropriate.

414
00:22:21,655 --> 00:22:22,758
We have a dress code here.

415
00:22:22,827 --> 00:22:24,172
No dresses and skirts,

416
00:22:24,241 --> 00:22:26,758
nothing provocative, no shorts,
no makeup, no jewelry.

417
00:22:26,827 --> 00:22:28,068
Only long pants and shirts

418
00:22:28,137 --> 00:22:29,793
with the appropriate
sleeve lengths are allowed.

419
00:22:29,862 --> 00:22:31,000
Now, why don't you get undressed

420
00:22:31,068 --> 00:22:32,827
and we'll finish
getting you settled in.

421
00:22:32,896 --> 00:22:35,000
What do you mean
get undressed?

422
00:22:35,068 --> 00:22:38,172
I mean, take your clothes off.

423
00:22:38,241 --> 00:22:40,000
Excuse me?

424
00:22:40,068 --> 00:22:41,275
Strip search, it's routine.

425
00:22:41,344 --> 00:22:42,827
Nothing to worry about, honest.

426
00:22:47,379 --> 00:22:49,310
Here. Put this off.

427
00:22:49,379 --> 00:22:51,965
We have five status levels
here at Meadowbrook.

428
00:22:52,034 --> 00:22:53,862
With each level you
get more privileges.

429
00:22:53,931 --> 00:22:55,206
You're at level one.

430
00:22:55,275 --> 00:22:57,344
Earn a hundred points and
you move to the next level.

431
00:22:57,413 --> 00:22:59,448
You just earned 10 points
for cooperating back there.

432
00:22:59,517 --> 00:23:01,068
See how easy it is?

433
00:23:01,137 --> 00:23:02,551
If you behave, you
get privileges.

434
00:23:02,620 --> 00:23:05,310
Phone calls privileges,
maybe even off grounds.

435
00:23:05,379 --> 00:23:06,793
Talking with other patients

436
00:23:06,862 --> 00:23:08,793
will be confined with social
hour, from three to four daily.

437
00:23:08,862 --> 00:23:09,896
That's all.

438
00:23:09,965 --> 00:23:11,275
While you're here,
there'll be no TV,

439
00:23:11,344 --> 00:23:13,827
no radio, no mail, no visitors.

440
00:23:15,482 --> 00:23:17,689
I think we better
get a grip on napping

441
00:23:17,758 --> 00:23:19,172
in the middle of the day.

442
00:23:19,241 --> 00:23:22,137
Thank You, Ms. Collins.
I will modify my behavior.

443
00:23:22,206 --> 00:23:23,689
Your dresser.

444
00:23:23,758 --> 00:23:25,344
Your bed.

445
00:23:25,413 --> 00:23:27,551
Now, if you follow the rules,

446
00:23:27,620 --> 00:23:30,827
you and I will get
along just fine, okay?

447
00:23:30,896 --> 00:23:32,241
Group in 15 minutes.

448
00:23:35,103 --> 00:23:36,379
Hey.

449
00:23:40,551 --> 00:23:43,758
Look, I can't
talk to you. Okay?

450
00:23:43,827 --> 00:23:44,793
Why not?

451
00:23:44,862 --> 00:23:46,379
Cause I don't wanna
lose any points.

452
00:23:46,448 --> 00:23:49,551
I'm almost on level four
then I get my own room.

453
00:23:49,620 --> 00:23:52,000
Fine, we don't have to talk.

454
00:23:54,034 --> 00:23:56,758
Did you get
anything past them?

455
00:23:56,827 --> 00:23:57,896
Like what?

456
00:23:57,965 --> 00:24:00,172
You know, cigarettes,
pot, anything ?

457
00:24:03,275 --> 00:24:04,275
[chuckles]

458
00:24:04,344 --> 00:24:06,034
You mean if I
wanted to believe me,

459
00:24:06,103 --> 00:24:07,034
they looked everywhere.

460
00:24:07,103 --> 00:24:09,103
There's ways around
that you'll see.

461
00:24:11,482 --> 00:24:12,620
[chuckles]

462
00:24:12,689 --> 00:24:16,000
At least you gotta little
buzz going there, right?

463
00:24:16,068 --> 00:24:18,965
Yeah. I feel like I've
been run over by a truck.

464
00:24:19,034 --> 00:24:21,827
You're doing the
"thighs-in shuffle", that's all.

465
00:24:21,896 --> 00:24:24,103
Just enough to mellow you out.

466
00:24:24,172 --> 00:24:27,517
If you didn't have a
drug problem coming in,

467
00:24:27,586 --> 00:24:29,689
don't worry you are going out.

468
00:24:34,034 --> 00:24:36,103
[CJ] And we had totally
different taste in music

469
00:24:36,172 --> 00:24:39,344
which was like this big
issue with my old man.

470
00:24:39,413 --> 00:24:42,310
I mean, he thought I was
worshiping devil or something.

471
00:24:42,379 --> 00:24:44,344
He was into all this...

472
00:24:44,413 --> 00:24:46,551
folk music, peace and love crap.

473
00:24:46,620 --> 00:24:48,275
With all of his friends
that wore sandals

474
00:24:48,344 --> 00:24:51,482
and sit far out all the time.

475
00:24:51,551 --> 00:24:53,689
I just couldn't take it anymore.

476
00:24:56,413 --> 00:24:58,241
So one day I took all
of his records out

477
00:24:58,310 --> 00:25:00,758
and busted them up with
a hammer in the garage.

478
00:25:02,827 --> 00:25:04,379
And how did that
make you feel?

479
00:25:06,344 --> 00:25:07,310
Felt great.

480
00:25:07,379 --> 00:25:08,448
[chuckles]

481
00:25:13,655 --> 00:25:15,448
[Marty] Oh.

482
00:25:15,517 --> 00:25:17,241
[Counselor] Yes Marty. You have
something you'd like to share?

483
00:25:17,310 --> 00:25:19,344
Well, I have a
complaint to register.

484
00:25:21,482 --> 00:25:23,103
Fine. What is it?

485
00:25:23,172 --> 00:25:24,310
Well, you know that
that blue water stuff

486
00:25:24,379 --> 00:25:25,620
they have in the toilets here?

487
00:25:25,689 --> 00:25:27,620
The commercial says it's
supposed to last 2000 flushes.

488
00:25:27,689 --> 00:25:29,206
Right? Well, I've been counting.

489
00:25:29,275 --> 00:25:32,034
With one night it can
only last 879 flushes.

490
00:25:32,103 --> 00:25:35,137
That's a difference
of like 1,121 flushes.

491
00:25:35,206 --> 00:25:36,793
That's false advertising.

492
00:25:36,862 --> 00:25:38,068
I mean, I say there
ought to be a law---

493
00:25:38,137 --> 00:25:39,793
[Counselor] Thank you Marty.

494
00:25:39,862 --> 00:25:41,206
Keep it up.

495
00:25:41,275 --> 00:25:43,931
You're gonna be at level two
for the rest of your life.

496
00:25:45,862 --> 00:25:48,379
Does anyone else have
words of wisdom to offer?

497
00:25:50,758 --> 00:25:53,344
All right, we have a
new member of our group

498
00:25:53,413 --> 00:25:54,517
joining us today.

499
00:25:54,586 --> 00:25:56,724
Stand up.

500
00:25:56,793 --> 00:26:00,000
You can introduce yourself to
everyone by stating your name

501
00:26:00,068 --> 00:26:02,896
and admitting that
you're an alcoholic.

502
00:26:02,965 --> 00:26:05,965
Alcoholic, what are
you talking about?

503
00:26:06,034 --> 00:26:08,827
You got into a run-in with
the police the other night.

504
00:26:08,896 --> 00:26:10,068
Crashed your car,

505
00:26:10,137 --> 00:26:11,758
it says right here that
you'd been drinking.

506
00:26:11,827 --> 00:26:13,275
That's a mistake.

507
00:26:13,344 --> 00:26:14,827
[chuckles]
I don't have a drinking problem.

508
00:26:14,896 --> 00:26:17,172
I don't even like
the taste of alcohol.

509
00:26:17,241 --> 00:26:18,586
Group?

510
00:26:18,655 --> 00:26:21,310
Denial.

511
00:26:21,379 --> 00:26:23,689
Denial

512
00:26:23,758 --> 00:26:24,965
Denial.

513
00:26:25,034 --> 00:26:26,137
Denial.

514
00:26:26,206 --> 00:26:28,551
[CJ]
You either face up or shut up.

515
00:26:28,620 --> 00:26:30,413
Those are the only two
choices you've got.

516
00:26:30,482 --> 00:26:32,137
[Counselor] CJ's right.

517
00:26:32,206 --> 00:26:34,103
The sooner you admit
that you have a problem,

518
00:26:34,172 --> 00:26:35,896
the sooner we can get
at some of the feelings

519
00:26:35,965 --> 00:26:36,724
that are at the source.

520
00:26:36,793 --> 00:26:38,275
Eh-- I'm not gonna stand here

521
00:26:38,344 --> 00:26:41,172
and say that I'm an
alcoholic when I'm not.

522
00:26:41,241 --> 00:26:43,896
Fine, your choice.

